phases.content:
Add an optional `action?: { label: string; onClick: () => void }` to the Toast API, render it as a compact button between the message and the dismiss control, and wire one real consumer to prove the pattern.

### API change — `apps/desktop/src/stores/toastStore.ts`

Extend the `Toast` interface (around lines 6–12):
```ts
export interface ToastAction {
  label: string;
  onClick: () => void;
}
export interface Toast {
  id: string;
  type: ToastType;
  message: string;
  duration: number;
  createdAt: number;
  action?: ToastAction;
}
```

Extend the `addToast` signature (currently `addToast(message, type, duration?)`) with a 4th optional parameter — **Option A from the review**: zero-disruption to ~12 existing callers, no overloads.
```ts
addToast: (message: string, type?: ToastType, duration?: number, action?: ToastAction) => string;
```

The action just gets attached to the stored Toast object; auto-dismiss timer and `removeToast` are unchanged.

### Render — `apps/desktop/src/components/ui/Toast.tsx`

Extend `ToastProps` to include the action (it already receives the full `toast` object — check the current props; if action lives on `toast.action`, no prop changes are needed, just access `toast.action` in the render).

Insert a button between the `toast-message` div and the `toast-close` button, conditional on `toast.action`:
```tsx
{toast.action && (
  <button
    type="button"
    className="toast-action"
    onClick={() => {
      try {
        toast.action!.onClick();
      } catch (err) {
        console.error("Toast action onClick threw:", err);
      } finally {
        onClose();
      }
    }}
  >
    {toast.action.label}
  </button>
)}
```

The try/catch + finally ensures the toast always dismisses even if the action callback throws (per review risk #3).

Tab order falls out naturally: action button (first DOM-order) → dismiss button.

### Styling — `apps/desktop/src/components/ui/Toast.css`

Add a `.toast-action` rule using the same neutral idiom as `.toast-close` but as a text-label button:
```css
.toast-action {
  flex-shrink: 0;
  padding: 0 8px;
  height: 22px;
  font-size: 11px;
  line-height: 1;
  color: var(--text-secondary);
  background: transparent;
  border: 1px solid var(--border-color);
  border-radius: 4px;
  cursor: pointer;
  transition: background 0.15s ease, color 0.15s ease;
}
.toast-action:hover {
  background: var(--bg-hover);
  color: var(--text-primary);
}
.toast-action:focus-visible {
  outline: 2px solid var(--accent-color);
  outline-offset: 1px;
}
```

### Proof-of-concept consumer — `apps/desktop/src/components/sidebar/ProjectsSection.tsx` (line 68 area)

The existing toast says "Tiki framework outdated for {project} — click the badge in the sidebar to update." There's an obvious in-app action (the badge click triggers `handleInstallFramework` in `ProjectCard.tsx:30+`). Wire the action.

Replace the existing toast call (around line 64–71) so it passes an `action`:
```tsx
useToastStore.getState().addToast(
  `Tiki framework outdated for ${activeProject.name} — click Update to install v${latest}`,
  "warning",
  8000,
  {
    label: "Update",
    onClick: () => {
      // Invoke the same install flow ProjectCard's badge click runs.
      // Use a custom event the badge handler subscribes to, OR (simpler)
      // expose `installFramework(projectPath)` from a shared util that both
      // ProjectCard and this consumer call. Pick whichever fits the existing
      // shape with the smallest diff — see Implementation note below.
    },
  }
);
```

**Implementation note on the action callback wiring:** Two practical options:
- **(a) Custom DOM event** — Dispatch `window.dispatchEvent(new CustomEvent("tiki:install-framework", { detail: { projectPath } }))` from the action; have `ProjectCard.tsx` add a `window.addEventListener` in a `useEffect` that calls the existing `handleInstallFramework`. Cleanest decoupling.
- **(b) Direct invocation** — Extract the install logic from `ProjectCard.tsx:30+` into a shared helper (e.g. `apps/desktop/src/utils/installFramework.ts`) and call it from both sites. Cleaner abstraction but a wider change.

**Use (a) — custom DOM event** — keeps the diff small (~10 lines added in ProjectCard.tsx for the listener, ~5 lines in ProjectsSection.tsx for the dispatch) and avoids extracting state and store dependencies into a helper.

For an even smaller first pass, if the listener approach in ProjectCard.tsx turns out to be awkward (e.g., it needs project context that isn't available from the event detail alone), the executor may fall back to a simpler real consumer:
- The existing **error toast** at App.tsx:69 (`addToast(\`Issue #${newItem.issue.number} failed\`, 'error', 8000)`) can carry an action `{ label: "View Issue", onClick: () => setSelectedIssue(newItem.issue) }`. That's a 3-line proof-of-concept that requires no new event plumbing — `setSelectedIssue` is already available in App.tsx's scope.

**Pick whichever lands cleaner.** The proof-of-concept goal is to demonstrate the pattern works in a real consumer — either site satisfies the acceptance criteria.

### Scope boundaries

- Four files at most: `toastStore.ts`, `Toast.tsx`, `Toast.css`, and ONE consumer site.
- No CSS framework changes; matches existing `--text-secondary`, `--border-color`, `--bg-hover`, `--accent-color` token usage.
- No new dependencies. Existing `~12 addToast call sites stay untouched (4th arg is optional).
- `updateToast` left alone (it only updates the message field today; per review risk #5).

### Test plan

- `pnpm build` — clean tsc -b + vite. Watch for TS6133 unused imports (the v0.5.4 regret pattern).
- `pnpm test` — 89 desktop vitest baseline preserved.
- Manual smoke: (a) trigger the framework-outdated warning by opening a project with a stale `.tiki/.framework-version` → toast appears with "Update" button → click it → install flow runs and the toast dismisses; (b) trigger any non-action toast → renders identically to before; (c) tab into the toast → action button focuses first, dismiss button second; (d) throw inside the action callback (developer test) → toast still dismisses, console.error visible.
